<subSubSection id="67895467AE843CA921B311B3D0363392" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="notes">
<paragraph id="AAFEF6EB1576DC9284D91A10E5D13AA4" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5129900C6C5525324713EA31CD6A9421" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
A formal proposal to conserve the name 
<taxonomicName id="0206D3164207E8E73D6FA2EE183B434F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chenopodium" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EEA359E4C62EE32E6AA3DA3129856A8C" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Chenopodium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. with the type 
<taxonomicName id="D370FCE6A4778E58A19D23CA1C465E3E" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl.: 219" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chenopodium album" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">
<emphasis id="9AEA4364392B9C00E7EE269DCF5FDA80" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Chenopodium album</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. has only recently been put forward (
<bibRefCitation id="8420F2418052FF8792DEE56B5E82666D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.12705/646.24" author="Mosyakin, SL" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" pagination="1323 - 1325" refId="B72" refString="Mosyakin, SL, 2015. Proposal to conserve the name Chenopodium (Chenopodiaceae s. str.; Amaranthaceae sensu APG) with a conserved type. Taxon 64 (6): 1323 - 1325, DOI: https://doi.org/10.12705/646.24" title="Proposal to conserve the name Chenopodium (Chenopodiaceae s. str.; Amaranthaceae sensu APG) with a conserved type." url="https://doi.org/10.12705/646.24" volume="64" year="2015">Mosyakin 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The conservation of the name with this type would be most desirable to maintain the recent taxonomy of 
<taxonomicName id="1AC18F3110010CE8EC2E51E9D6FBD1A9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chenopodium" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65292E0DED31260B8B82C74EA874EF47" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Chenopodium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its relatives, especially 
<taxonomicName id="7DD553CC227AAA7167CE903E7E2292C1" authorityName="Kar. &amp; Kir., Bull. Soc. Imp. Nat. Moscou [14]: 738" authorityYear="1841" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Oxybasis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oxybasis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DF9EA7CCE74BAD96DFD2618209B842A8" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Oxybasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F59A6160C8C64A3F03EEFA48D5954E28" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="15" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="description">
<paragraph id="9B5E47B5481F3AFF3EB1EDDBBCC7EBF2" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B3CFF4EC3C644A42D8F6CDBB3EC71B86" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Annuals, shrubs, or rarely small trees, covered with bladder hairs. Leaves petiolate, usually lobed or dentate (sometimes entire), very rarely semi-terete. Inflorescences paniculate, composed of small cymose clusters. Flowers sessile and pedicellate, hermaphrodite or some female. Perianth segments 5 (rarely 4), free or basally concrescent, green and unchanging at fruiting. Stamens usually 5, free or basally connate. Stigmas 2, free. Fruit depressed globular, falling off separately or together with perianth. Pericarp mostly thin, hyaline, of 1-2(3) parenchymatous layers, usually with small cylindrical or conical papillae (in dry fruits, the pericarp surface resembles honeycombs, but after soaking, the papillae retrieve their shape). In some species now transferred from 
<taxonomicName id="EECBCB013375B27C1A3FCBDB49263D87" authorityName="Rafinesque" authorityYear="1838" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="Einadia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Einadia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2D9533E51D368ADC027A0ACB2964B23F" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Einadia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="3AA3CCAA291381E3B4BE68DDB94D484D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chenopodium" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7BD16788D909EEB6C4ECA995685F8A7D" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Chenopodium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the pericarp (at least in most fruits) is fleshy (berry), coloured, and many-layered, but some of the fruits remain dry (heterocarpy). Seeds black or rarely brown with horizontal embryo; the cell walls of testa (outer seed-coat layer) cells in black seeds with vertical stalactites, rarely the stalactites absent (three species from 
<normalizedToken id="62A160AECDF7D79F3FF77302096FEF53" originalValue="Juan-Fernández">Juan-Fernandez</normalizedToken>
Archipelago).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B4C4488D1E1C2A0C3ACC4DE23BAD0029" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<pageBreakToken id="DD1ECA3B18488338651382FAF105A932" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" start="start">In</pageBreakToken>
its current circumscription (
<bibRefCitation id="C472D8596BF0213A3C7267691EE3B43C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.006" author="Fuentes, S" journalOrPublisher="172. Akademische Druck- und Verlagsanstalt, Graz" pageId="125" pageNumber="126" refId="B26" refString="Fuentes, S, Mansion, G, Borsch, T, 2012. Towards a species level tree of the globally diverse genus Chenopodium. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 62(1): 359-374. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.006" title="Towards a species level tree of the globally diverse genus Chenopodium. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 62 (1): 359 - 374." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.006" year="2012">Fuentes et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
), the genus comprises more than 100 species, but the exact number is still unknown. The species are mostly distributed in extratropical parts of the world or in mountainous regions of the tropics.
</paragraph>
